<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910424-0149</DOCNO><DOCID>910424-0149.</DOCID><HL>   American Express to Join   Sumitomo in Card Venture</HL><DATE>04/24/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C11</SO><CO>   AXP J.STB</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, CREDIT INSTITUTIONS (FIS)</IN><RE>JAPAN (JA)NEW YORK (NY)</RE><LP>   TOKYO -- American Express Co. agreed with Sumitomo BankLtd., Japan's third-largest bank, to establish a jointventure to issue and market charge cards in Japan.   Under the agreement, to be signed today, each companywould assume a 50% partnership in a new company that willissue American Express Gold Cards to Sumitomo's customers inJapan. The venture, Amex Sumigin Service Co., will becapitalized at 240 million yen ($1.7 million) and will beginoperations this summer, officials said.</LP><TEXT>   American Express, based in New York, said the venture isan effort to hurdle distribution obstacles. American Expresshas issued just over one million cards in Japan since 1980.To date, its marketing efforts have focused on direct mailcampaigns and card-application displays in bars andrestaurants.   Archrival Visa International, based in San Francisco, hasbeen considerably more successful. Through a web ofrelationships with Japanese financial institutions, Visa hasissued cards to 33 million Japanese.   In the new venture, Sumitomo will promote Gold Cards atits 377 branch offices in Japan, while American Express willconcentrate on advertising, accounting and customer service.</TEXT></DOC>